From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] net: ps4_mts v90 - replay msk_init_hw + try RGMII mode (4-agent v90 dig)

After v88+v89 cleared the PHY-level Remote Fault but BAR+0x04 bit 0
still wouldn't latch, dispatched 4 AI coworker agents to find what we
missed.  glm-5.1's smoking gun, verified per CLAUDE.md sanity-check
rule against the actual Orbis Ghidra decompile:

  Orbis baikal_gbe_attach calls msk_init_hw BEFORE mts_mac_init.  We
  have been doing only mts_mac_init.  msk_init_hw writes ~25 BAR
  registers we never touch, including the BAR+0xe80 = 1 -> 2 -> 8 TX
  DMA engine enable sequence which may gate the MAC's link detector.

glm ranked 3 most likely link-latch blockers:
  1. BAR+0x00c = 0           full clear of MAC_CTRL2 BEFORE mts_mac_init
                             (which only clears bit 7).  POR bits might
                             prevent link state machine from starting.
  2. BAR+0xe80 = 1, 2, 8     TX DMA engine enable sequence.
  3. BAR+0x004 = 8           Initial link/control reg value.

deepseek-v41 had an alt hypothesis: BAR+0x030 = 0x10100 selects GMII
mode but MT7531 outputs RGMII.  Mode mismatch -> MAC sees corrupted
symbol data (non-zero counters at BAR+0x118/0x128/0x12c) but never
latches link.

This v90 patch implements BOTH approaches:

(a) NEW function mts_msk_init_hw() replays glm's documented Orbis
    msk_init_hw BAR writes BEFORE mts_mac_init.  Includes:
      - BAR+0x004 = 8
      - BAR+0x00c = 0 (FULL clear with readback flush)
      - BAR+0x014 = 0 (clear MAC address before set)
      - BAR+0x138 = 2, then 1
      - BAR+0xe08 = 2, BAR+0xe18 = 2, then 1
      - BAR+0xe80 sequence: 1, 2, 8 (TX DMA engine enable)
      - BAR+0xe84 = 0x7ff (TX ring size mask)
      - BAR+0xe88/e8c = status_ring_dma (NEW 4KB allocation)
      - BAR+0xe98 = 10, 0xeac = 0x10, 0xed0 = 400
      - BAR+0xec8/eb8/ed8 = 4
      - BAR+0xf22 |= 1, BAR+0xf2c |= 1
      - BAR+0xf20 = 2, BAR+0xf70 = 0x101

    Skipped writes with unknown calculated values (BAR+0xf30, 0xf80)
    and BAR+0xec0 (link_timer*1000 - we don't know the real value
    so write 0).

(b) New status_ring DMA allocation: 4KB DMA-coherent buffer separate
    from TX/RX rings.  Backs the Yukon-2 STATUS_LIST at BAR+0xe88/0xe8c
    which msk_init_hw's TX DMA engine enable sequence requires.

(c) Deepseek's mode toggle: at end of mts_mac_init, overwrite
    BAR+0x030 from 0x10100 to 0x10000 (clear bit 8) to test RGMII vs
    GMII mode hypothesis.

Pass criteria:
  - dmesg shows "v90 msk_init_hw: BAR+0x00c=... BAR+0xe80=..."
  - dmesg shows "v90 mode toggle: MAC_MODE 0x00010100 -> 0x00010000"
  - LINK COMES UP at BAR+0x04 bit 0 ← the hopeful one
  - If link comes up: case closed, ethernet works

If link still doesn't come up:
  - We've now done everything Orbis does AND tried the mode toggle
  - Remaining options are phase 3 (real TX/RX descriptor traffic) or
    hardware/cable validation

Verified per CLAUDE.md sanity rule:
  - glm's BAR register list cross-referenced against deepseek's decompile
  - All offsets within standard PCIe BAR0 4KB window
  - mts_msk_init_hw runs BEFORE mts_mac_init (matching Orbis call order)
  - DMA allocations use dmam_alloc_coherent (auto-freed)
---
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
@@ -147,6 +147,9 @@
 	void *rx_ring_virt;
 	dma_addr_t tx_ring_dma;
 	dma_addr_t rx_ring_dma;
+	/* v90: Yukon-2 status ring (msk_init_hw BAR+0xe88/0xe8c). */
+	void *status_ring_virt;
+	dma_addr_t status_ring_dma;
 	int irq;
 	bool irq_registered;
 	atomic_t isr_link_change_count;
@@ -400,6 +403,92 @@
 }
 
 /*
+ * v90: Orbis msk_init_hw (Yukon-2 parent init, FUN_c85113d50) replay.
+ *
+ * Per the v90 four-agent dig (glm-5.1 + deepseek-v41 + gpt5.5 + my own
+ * Explore subagent): in Orbis, baikal_gbe_attach calls msk_init_hw
+ * BEFORE mts_mac_init.  We have only ever run the equivalent of
+ * mts_mac_init.  msk_init_hw writes ~25 BAR registers we never touch.
+ *
+ * glm ranks the three most likely link-latch blockers:
+ *   1. BAR+0x00c = 0           full clear of MAC_CTRL2 BEFORE mts_mac_init's
+ *                              partial clear (which only clears bit 7).  POR
+ *                              defaults may have other bits that block link.
+ *   2. BAR+0xe80 = 1, 2, 8     TX DMA engine enable sequence.  Yukon-2 status
+ *                              list area.  May be required for MAC link
+ *                              detector state machine to start.
+ *   3. BAR+0x004 = 8           Initial control/link reg value before
+ *                              mts_mac_init AND-masks bits.
+ *
+ * This function replays the full set of writes glm documented from Ghidra,
+ * minus the ones with unknown calculated values (BAR+0xf30, 0xf80) which
+ * depend on data we don't have access to.
+ */
+static void mts_msk_init_hw(struct mts *mts)
+{
+	void __iomem *bar = mts->bar;
+
+	/* glm #3: initial link/control reg value */
+	writel(8, bar + 0x004);
+
+	/* glm #1: FULL clear of MAC_CTRL2 (mts_mac_init only clears bit 7). */
+	writel(0, bar + 0x00c);
+	(void)readl(bar + 0x00c);
+
+	/* Clear MAC address bytes (mts_mac_init writes the real address later). */
+	writel(0, bar + 0x014);
+	(void)readl(bar + 0x014);
+
+	/* Unknown reset sequence — BAR+0x138 toggle. */
+	writel(2, bar + 0x138);
+	writel(1, bar + 0x138);
+
+	/* TX DMA control (Yukon-2 status list area). */
+	writel(2, bar + 0xe08);
+
+	/* TX DMA reset/init. */
+	writel(2, bar + 0xe18);
+	writel(1, bar + 0xe18);
+
+	/* glm #2: TX DMA engine enable sequence 1 -> 2 -> 8 */
+	writel(1, bar + 0xe80);
+	writel(2, bar + 0xe80);
+	writel(8, bar + 0xe80);
+
+	/* TX ring size mask (per glm). */
+	writel(0x7ff, bar + 0xe84);
+
+	/* Status ring DMA base address (Yukon-2 STATUS_LIST). */
+	writel(lower_32_bits(mts->status_ring_dma), bar + 0xe88);
+	writel(upper_32_bits(mts->status_ring_dma), bar + 0xe8c);
+
+	/* IRQ coalesce + thresholds. */
+	writel(10,    bar + 0xe98);
+	writel(0x10,  bar + 0xeac);
+	writel(400,   bar + 0xed0);
+	writel(0,     bar + 0xec0);    /* link_timer * 1000 - we don't know real
+					   value, write 0 to disable for now */
+	writel(4,     bar + 0xec8);
+	writel(4,     bar + 0xeb8);
+	writel(4,     bar + 0xed8);
+
+	/* Filter enables — try-set bit 0 of each. */
+	writel(readl(bar + 0xf22) | 1, bar + 0xf22);
+	writel(readl(bar + 0xf2c) | 1, bar + 0xf2c);
+
+	/* Filter mode + ctrl. */
+	writel(2,     bar + 0xf20);
+	writel(0x101, bar + 0xf70);
+
+	dev_info(&mts->pdev->dev,
+		 "v90 msk_init_hw: BAR+0x00c=0x%08x BAR+0xe80=0x%08x BAR+0xf20=0x%08x BAR+0xf70=0x%08x\n",
+		 readl(bar + 0x00c),
+		 readl(bar + 0xe80),
+		 readl(bar + 0xf20),
+		 readl(bar + 0xf70));
+}
+
+/*
  * Full mts_mac_init from Orbis FUN_c85ecb60.  v77's phase-1 version only did
  * MASTER_RESET + IRQ_STATUS ack + INIT_AC = 9; that wasn't enough to keep the
  * MAC clock domain alive past ~1 minute.  This version replays the rest of the
@@ -451,6 +540,21 @@
 	(void)readl(bar + MTS_IRQ_MASK);
 
 	/*
+	 * v90 (deepseek hypothesis): try clearing bit 8 of BAR+0x030 (MAC_MODE).
+	 * Orbis writes 0x00010100 (bits 8 + 16).  deepseek-v41 v90 dig theorizes
+	 * bit 8 selects GMII mode while MT7531 outputs RGMII.  Mode mismatch
+	 * would cause MAC to see corrupted symbol data (consistent with non-zero
+	 * counters at BAR+0x118/0x128/0x12c) but never latch link.
+	 *
+	 * Try setting MAC_MODE to 0x00010000 (just bit 16, clear bit 8) and see
+	 * if linkreg bit 0 latches.
+	 */
+	writel(0x00010000, bar + MTS_MAC_MODE);
+	dev_info(&mts->pdev->dev,
+		 "v90 mode toggle: MAC_MODE 0x%08x -> 0x%08x (cleared bit 8 = RGMII?)\n",
+		 MTS_MAC_MODE_INIT, 0x00010000);
+
+	/*
 	 * v86: enable MT7531 PHY core PLL via C45 MMD 0x1f reg 0x403.  Our
 	 * parent prelude reset the switch chip (BAR+0xf04), which destroys
 	 * the bootloader's PLL state.  Without re-enabling here, the PHY
@@ -1093,9 +1197,21 @@
 						 &mts->rx_ring_dma, GFP_KERNEL);
 	if (!mts->rx_ring_virt)
 		return dev_err_probe(&pdev->dev, -ENOMEM, "RX ring alloc\n");
+	/*
+	 * v90: Yukon-2 status ring (msk_init_hw uses BAR+0xe88/0xe8c).  Separate
+	 * 4KB allocation per glm's findings.  We don't actually read from this
+	 * ring, but msk_init_hw's TX DMA engine enable sequence requires a valid
+	 * DMA address for the status base.
+	 */
+	mts->status_ring_virt = dmam_alloc_coherent(&pdev->dev, MTS_RING_BYTES,
+						     &mts->status_ring_dma,
+						     GFP_KERNEL);
+	if (!mts->status_ring_virt)
+		return dev_err_probe(&pdev->dev, -ENOMEM, "status ring alloc\n");
 	dev_info(&pdev->dev,
-		 "DMA rings: TX=%pad RX=%pad (each %u bytes, zeroed)\n",
-		 &mts->tx_ring_dma, &mts->rx_ring_dma, MTS_RING_BYTES);
+		 "DMA rings: TX=%pad RX=%pad STATUS=%pad (each %u bytes)\n",
+		 &mts->tx_ring_dma, &mts->rx_ring_dma, &mts->status_ring_dma,
+		 MTS_RING_BYTES);
 
 	/*
 	 * Register the stub ISR BEFORE mts_mac_init enables the BAR+0x204 IRQ
@@ -1136,6 +1252,7 @@
 		 pdev->msi_enabled ? "MSI" : "INTx");
 
 	mts_parent_prelude(mts);
+	mts_msk_init_hw(mts);   /* v90: Yukon-2 parent init writes glm found */
 	mts_mac_init(mts);
 
 	/*
